Trainer Hill

The Trainer Hill, located in Route 111, is a battle facility accessible only in Emerald. In this facility, Trainers can take up to six Pokémon into a series of Double Battles separated by floor, with a total of four floors. This facility was originally intended to be used with e-Reader cards; scanning e-Reader cards would change the enemy Trainers and Pokémon that the player would fight on each floor of the tower. As the e-Reader did not receive much support outside of Japan, the ability to use e-Reader cards was removed from international releases of Emerald, and the player instead fights predetermined Trainers based on some of the data provided by the original e-Reader cards.

Battle Mechanics

In this facility, items can be used outside battle, and the player can actually return to the entrance of the hill in order to heal their Pokémon during the challenge. The catch is that the player is rewarded an item for completing the tower within a certain time limit; returning to heal Pokémon will make this time limit harder to maintain.

No EXP or prize money is gained for battles fought in the Trainer Hill. The level of all of the opposing Pokémon will match the level of the player's highest-leveled Pokémon. The enemy Pokémon will always have predetermined EVs, IVs, and movesets regardless of their level.

The moves Thief, Covet, and Trick will fail here.

Return, Frustration, and Hidden Power all have maximum power.

Mode Mechanics

All battles conducted in this facility are Double Battles, although it is possible to turn some of them into Single Battles by speaking to one of the two Trainers instead of walking between them.

In international versions of Emerald, entering the Trainer Hill allows the player to choose which of four modes to challenge: Normal, Variety, Unique, and Expert Mode. Each mode choice contains a static set of Trainers that the player will fight, and offers a different prize for finishing the challenge quickly.

Poké Mart

The Poké Mart here sells two separate stocks of items, one before the player defeats the Elite Four and one after. In international versions of Emerald, the Trainer Hill cannot be entered until after the Elite Four have been defeated, so the first stock goes unused.

Prizes

For defeating the chosen challenge within a certain time limit, the player will receive a prize. In every challenge, a grand prize can be received for defeating the challenge within 12 minutes. Which item is received as the grand prize will depend on which Trainers the player defeated during the challenge. This means, in international versions of Emerald, the grand prize will always be the same, but in the Japanese version, it will depend on which e-Reader cards were scanned.

The following table shows the prizes other than the grand prize:

13-14 Max Potion

18+ Great Ball

Data

The rest of the page contains three sections: one containing the international releases' static Trainer data; one containing the Japanese releases' default Trainers (which occupy only two floors instead of four), and one containing all the known e-Reader card data for enemy Trainers. As the enemy Pokémon can be any level, their IVs and EVs are given instead of a stat. To calculate their stats, you can use a calculator such as Pokémon Showdown's; select "ADV" as the generation.

e-Reader Trainer Data

e-Reader cards can only be scanned in the Japanese releases of Emerald. Scanning e-Reader cards replaces the default trainers with data for other trainers, dependent on which card is scanned. Although the default Trainer Hill in Japanese releases is only two floors, scanning e-Reader cards allows for up to four floors. Prizes will only be awarded for a challenge that covers all four floors.

Each Trainer has a party with six Pokémon, even though any individual Trainer fought in the Hill will only have three Pokémon. The Trainer Hill is set up to choose either the first or last three Pokémon in the Trainer's party depending on whether they are technically the first or second trainer fought in the Double Battle.

If the player scans an odd number of e-Reader cards, data for an additional Trainer will be supplied in order to force an even number of Trainers to make Double Battles possible. Each floor has a predetermined default Trainer. The four default Trainers are shown below.
